#!/bin/sh
# SH FILE: info-gcc
#
# Purpose   : Print information about GCC tooling.
# Created   : Wednesday, July 24 2024.
# Author    : Pierre Rouleau <prouleau001@gmail.com>
# Time-stamp: <2026-02-18 17:00:40 EST, updated by Pierre Rouleau>
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Module Description
# ------------------
#

# Preliminary version of a tool to help investigate GCC built systems.  It
# currently prints information about the tools on stdout command -v in itself is
# already useful.

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Dependencies
# ------------
#
# gcc, printf

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Code
# ----
#
#
printf -- "The GCC programs:\n"
printf -- "\
:Ref: GCC Architecture overview:
   https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/GNU_C_Compiler_Internals/GNU_C_Compiler_Architecture

- cc1     : internal command that takes pre-processed C-language files
            and converts them to assembly.
- cc1plus : internal command that takes pre-processed C++ language files
            and convert them to assembly.
Locations:
- cc1    : %s

- cc1plus: %s

- cc     : %s
         : %s
  : %s

- gcc    : %s
         : %s
  : %s

- g++    : %s
         : %s
  : %s

You may want to invoke these programs with  the -v switch to see the include
path used.  You will have to provide an END-OF-FILE signal (Ctrl-D) to stop
the programs.

INCLUDE PATH:

To identify the directories where the compiler gets the C and C++ header
files, use the following commands:

- For C   : \`gcc -print-prog-name=cpp\` -v      < /dev/null
- For C++ : \`gcc -print-prog-name=cc1plus\` -v  < /dev/null

The output of these 2 commands are verbose but it identifies the correct
directories.
" \
       "$(gcc -print-prog-name=cc1)"            \
       "$(gcc -print-prog-name=cc1plus)"        \
       "$(command -v cc)"                       \
       "$(cc --version | head -1)"              \
       "$(ls -l "$(command -v cc)")"            \
       "$(command -v gcc)"                      \
       "$(gcc --version | head -1)"             \
       "$(ls -l "$(command -v gcc)")"           \
       "$(command -v g++)"                      \
       "$(g++ --version | head -1)"             \
       "$(ls -l "$(command -v g++)")"

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Local Variables:
# sh-shell: /bin/sh
# End:
